metadata.name: string_pllu #6
metadata.description:
Making some abstract plants, inspired by a painting technique called string pull.

Connect some random semi circles with strings and pull the strings from the bottom of the canvas.

The semi circles rotate while moving to create some random brush strokes.

metadata.name: Self, Id #19
metadata.description:
The first installment of the Self trilogy.

Id is defined as: the one of the three divisions of the psyche in psychoanalytic theory that is completely unconscious and is the source of psychic energy derived from instinctual needs and drives.

Please see attached fx(text) article or go to https://ty-vek.art/self-trilogy for more on concept/mechanics/etc. It’s a bit of long read, but worth it.

—————————

All projects are written in vanilla Javascript, composed as SVG and then rendered to a 2d canvas.

There might be slight differences in rendering from browser to browser. This is expected as they might translate the SVG slightly differently. Let's call Chromium renderings canonical. They also render faster there and we love that.

Press "S" to save a PNG.
Press "V" to save a SVG. (Chromium browsers render these pretty well.)

By default, these will render at 2400 x 3200 pixels. This is at density 1.

To render at a larger resolution you can append “&d=2” to the end of the url. This will double the resolution. You can also use 3 or 4 or whatever your browser can handle. Safari tends to have problems with this, so stick with Chromium based browsers (Chrome, Edge, Brave, etc.)

If you want to render as a square image, so it is optimized for ummm.. your pfp or something, you can append “&sq=t” to the url.

If you want to get rid of grain, just append “&g=n”

—————————

https://ty-vek.art/self-trilogy
https://twitter.com/ty__vek
https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/Ty%20Vek/articles

objkt.name: THE WORD AFTER US: An AI poetry unreading #449

metadata.name: THE WORD AFTER US: An AI poetry unreading #449
metadata.description:
“Where in the world will words go, 
after us? How will they be arranged, 
and what will they sound like
when they arrive at their destination?
What will they be doing?
What will the world be doing?
Will the words be quiet or loud?
Will they be full of themselves,
or full of longing,
or full of longing’s opposite?”
 
An ars poetica on the future of literature and humanity. 
 
This project is a one-time generative poetry performance of a transhuman text by Sasha Stiles and her AI alter ego, Technelegy – read and unread by an algorithm authored by Nathaniel Stern. Every hash transforms one of 353 lines of AI-written poetry from legible letters into wordless language, generating a unique textblock from millions of possible combinations; each algorithmic translation unwrites itself, forever. Press "s" to overlay and toggle the original line of verse, and watch its shapes and meanings degenerate – or evolve – into an infinite visual poem.
 
All minters will receive an airdropped broadside (mp4) of the entire original poem after the performance is complete. A 1/1 media-rich audiovisual version of THE WORD AFTER US will also be made available.

 
Poetic traits:
- 353 possible lines of generative poetry produced by a GPT-3 language model fine-tuned on Stiles’ and Stern’s writing and research.
- 28 possible color palette combinations selected from Stern’s performative scanner art, with rare palettes including RGB, Hacker, Charcoal, and Chalkboard (black background).
- 6 possible fonts, including the premiere of Stern and Stiles’ custom AI font, NNFT (Neural Network Font Type), developed for their ongoing collaboration, “Mother Computer.”
- millions of layout and layering possibilities, including a rare “spiral” effect.
- billions of animation attribute combinations, which carry on forever.

metadata.name: A Lullaby for Euclid #29
metadata.description:
Geometric figures move in pendulous loops as they swirl through the scribbling winds of infinite (pseudo) randomly generated numbers.

The plot is simple, but the story lasts forever.

Controls
Press [p] to pause/unpause, or tap the image on a mobile device
Press [r] to restart the animation
Press [s] to save a copy of the current frame
Add “?pd=4” to the URL to reload at a higher pixel density

metadata.name: Wires #83
metadata.description:
Cut, pulled, twisted wires.
Some reach their destination, others will never arrive.
Wires forming weaves and figures, sometimes linear, sometimes chaotic but, in their simplicity they create harmonious intertwining.

Press "p" to pause, press again "p" to start again.
Press "s" to save as jpg.

Generative artwork by Gandhiavelli, @gandhiavelli. Made with p5js in 2022.
License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: "Dynamic Pathways".svg #9
metadata.description:
This artwork is combining cyberpunk and abstract art, bringing together the color palettes, futuristic motifs, and bold designs and artefacts that define each genre.

The outcome is an SVG that can be saved by pressing the "s" key. Created using pure JavaScript, without any dependencies.

Moreover, the fact that this piece was created through a collaboration with artificial intelligence adds an extra layer of cyberpunk flair to the work.

metadata.name: Cogito Ergo Contra Bellum #211
metadata.description:
Support Ukraine, replace your avatar with generative artwork! 📌Each piece is 100% unique, just like each of us, but we are all similar in that we are against war!📌

- Press 's' key in live mode to save in png.

Let's make our resistance visible together!

'Cogito Ergo Contra Bellum' ('I think, therefore I am against war,' René Descartes + Cardboard Carroll) generative PFP collection was created in support of the independence of Ukraine.

P.S.: I'll burn the rest of the collection when the war is over.

metadata.name: Artificial Flower 2 (2022), walkers series #8
metadata.description:
The first version was made at 2016 year. That time I was experiment with random walkers. The idea behind this sketch is the same with some my other artworks: create visual complex result with the basic rules that sometimes has references to the classic generative art technics by repeating a lot of iterations and mixing that classic technics with new possibilities that p5js brings – currently for that sketch is "random walker" technics and p5js color mixing and change alpha channel.

The first name of this sketch was "Painter walk" but I'm think that it's more looks like a flower, Artificial Flower.

Randomisation based on hash:
1. Color1 and Color2, that randomly selected from the list of 10 colors. If Color1 and Color2 can't be the same color, but sometimes it can be the darker or lighter version of the same color may create 3D effect (alpha also make such effect).
2. Amount of walkers (lines)
3. Each walker has uniq size, lifespan and walk path
4. I hope that I didn't forgot to mention something that also use fxhash randomisation.

The v1 can be found at https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/4439

I hope you will like it. Soon I will publish more new sketches and than adapt and publish my old sketches that was made in period from 2012 to 2019 year. Some of artworks from my profile are new. This one is remake of my old sketch that was made in 2016.

Thanks.

metadata.name: overloaded #55
metadata.description: Overloaded attempts to be a system to explore time perception, through non-representative images, while still representing pixels as upscaled forms. It plays with permanence and non-permanence.

metadata.name: Rooted #1
metadata.description:
"Rooted" is part of the live minting experience at Non Fungible Conference Lisbon, June 7-8, 2023.

—

Home is more than where we live, it is where we belong. It is where we are safe. Home does not belong to us, we belong to it. As I stand in wildflower meadows and watch the sun cross mountain peaks, I am home.

—

This project is a collaboration between artist, algorithm, and collector. The minters’ wallet address and fx(params) are used in place of a transaction hash for seeding random values, resulting in a WYSIWYG minting experience.
